===Flag===
[[File:Medal of Honor Flag with Gold Fringe.svg|thumb|Medal of Honor Flag]]
On October 23, 2002, {{USPL|107|248}} was enacted, modifying {{UnitedStatesCode|36|903}}, authorizing a Medal of Honor flag to be presented to recipients of the decoration.<ref name="flaglaw">{{cite web|date = 23 October 2002 |url = http://uscode.house.gov/download/pls/36C9.txt |title = Designation of the Medal of Honor Flag |publisher = US Code.gov |accessdate = July 23, 2006}}</ref>

The flag was based on a concept by retired [[U.S. Army Special Forces|Army Special Forces]] First Sergeant Bill Kendall of [[Jefferson, Iowa]],<ref name="Kendall">{{cite web|url = http://www4.army.mil/news/article.php?story=7244|title = Special Forces veteran's idea leads to new Medal of Honor flag |publisher = Army News Service|accessdate = July 24, 2006|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060111151709/http://www4.army.mil/news/article.php?story=7244 |archivedate = January 11, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref> who designed a flag to honor Medal of Honor recipient Captain [[Darrell Lindsey]], a [[B-26 Marauder|B-26]] pilot from Jefferson who was killed in World War II. Kendall's design of a light blue field emblazoned with 13 white five-pointed stars was nearly identical to that of Sarah LeClerc's of the [[U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry|Institute of Heraldry]]. LeClerc's design, ultimately accepted as the official flag, does not include the words "Medal of Honor" and is fringed in gold. The color of the field and the 13 white stars, arranged in the form of a three bar [[Chevron (insignia)|chevron]], consisting of two chevrons of five stars and one chevron of three stars,<ref name="regulations"/> replicate the suspension ribbon of the Medal of Honor. The flag has no set proportions.<ref name="flag">{{cite web|url = http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Flags_Guidons/MedalOfHonorFlag.htm |title = Medal of Honor Flag |work = The Institute of Heraldry |publisher = US Army |accessdate = July 21, 2006| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060911012812/http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Flags_Guidons/MedalOfHonorFlag.htm| archivedate = September 11, 2006}}</ref>

* The first Medal of Honor recipient to receive the official Medal of Honor flag was [[Sergeant First Class]] [[Paul R. Smith]]. The Medal of Honor with the flag was presented by [[President George W. Bush]] to his family during a ceremony at the [[White House]] on April 4, 2005.<ref name="smithflag">{{cite web|last = Cramer |first = Eric W. |date = March 29, 2005 |url = http://www4.army.mil/ocpa/read.php?story_id_key=7085 |title = First Medal of Honor flag to be presented |work = Army News Service |publisher = US Army|accessdate = July 21, 2006|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060721040551/http://www4.army.mil/ocpa/read.php?story_id_key=7085 |archivedate = July 21, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

A special Medal of Honor Flag presentation ceremony was held for over 60 living Medal of Honor recipients on board the {{USS|Constitution}} on September 30, 2006.<ref name="flagpresent">{{cite web|year = 2006 |url = http://www.news.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=25834 |title = "Old Ironsides" Hosts Medal of Honor Recipients |work = Navy Newsstand |publisher = US Navy |accessdate = October 1, 2006}}</ref>

==Presenting==
[[File:Henry Breault2.jpg|right|thumb|President [[Calvin Coolidge]] bestowing the Medal of Honor upon [[Henry Breault]], March 8, 1924]]
There are two distinct protocols for awarding the Medal of Honor. The first and most common is nomination and approval through the [[chain of command]] of the service member. The second method is nomination by a member of the U.S. Congress, generally at the request of a constituent, and the subsequent approval via a special [[Act of Congress]]. In both cases, the Medal of Honor is presented by the President on behalf of, and in the name of, the Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh.html |title=Medal of Honor Citations |publisher=History.army.mil |date=June 4, 2008 |accessdate=January 3, 2012}}</ref> Since 1941, more than half of the Medals of Honor have been awarded posthumously.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marine posthumously awarded Medal of Honor |author=Jeff Schogol |author2=Leoo Shane III |url=http://www.stripes.com/news/marine-posthumously-awarded-medal-of-honor-1.59068 |newspaper=Stars and Stripes |date=12 January 2007 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |quote=At the ceremony, Bush noted that more than half of the Medal of Honor recipients since World War II have died earning it. }}</ref> Medal of Honor recipients are usually personally decorated by the President.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.c-span.org/Events/Medal-of-Honor-Recipients-Tell-Their-Stories/10737435807/ |title=Medal of Honor Recipients Tell Their Stories |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=21 November 2012 |work=C-SPAN |publisher=National Cable Satellite Corporation |accessdate=28 January 2013 |quote=The Medal of Honor is the highest U.S. military honor and is usually presented by the President of the United States. }}</ref> If the Medal of Honor is awarded posthumously it is presented to the recipient's family.<ref>{{usc|10|3752}}</ref>

===Evolution of criteria===
* 1800s: Several months after President Abraham Lincoln signed Public Resolution 82 into law on December 21, 1861 for a Navy medal of honor, a similar resolution was passed in July 1862 for an Army version of the medal. Six [[Union Army]] soldiers who [[Great Locomotive Chase|hijacked]] a [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] [[locomotive]] named the ''[[General]]'' in 1862, were the first [[Medal of Honor recipients]];<ref name="MWxvii">{{harvnb|Mikaelian|Wallace|2003|p=xvii}}</ref> [[James J. Andrews]], a civilian, led the raid. He was caught and hanged as a Union spy, but was not awarded the medal. Many Medals of Honor awarded in the 19th century were associated with, "saving the flag" (and country), not just for patriotic reasons, but because the [[U.S. flag]] was a primary means of battlefield communication at the time. Because no other military decoration was authorized during the Civil War, some seemingly less exceptional and notable actions were recognized by a Medal of Honor during that conflict.

* 1900s: Early in the 20th century, the Navy awarded many Medals of Honor for peacetime bravery. For instance, in 1901, [[John Henry Helms]] aboard the {{USS|Chicago|CA-14}} was awarded the medal for saving the ship's cook from drowning. Seven sailors aboard the {{USS|Iowa|BB-4}} were awarded the medal after the ship's boiler exploded on January 25, 1904. [[Richard Evelyn Byrd|Richard Byrd]] and [[Floyd Bennett]] were awarded the medal after [[World War I]] for the exploration of the [[North Pole]].<ref name="HargisSinton2003">{{cite book|last1=argis|first1=Robert H|last2=Sinton|first2=Starr |title=World War II Medal of Honor recipients (1): Navy & USMC|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JdGr1QFy9HwC&pg=PA6|accessdate=March 14, 2012|year=2003|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84176-613-3|page=6}}</ref> And, [[Thomas J. Ryan (admiral)|Admiral Thomas J. Ryan]] was awarded the medal for saving a woman from the burning Grand Hotel in [[Yokohama]], Japan, following the 1923 [[Great Kant<U+014D> earthquake]].<ref name="ryan">{{cite web|url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/interim1920-40.html |title = Medal of Honor Recipients, Interim Awards 1920<U+2013>1940 |publisher = [[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate = July 23, 2006}}</ref> Between 1919 and 1942, the Navy issued two separate versions of the Medal of Honor, one for acts related to combat and one for non-combat bravery. The criteria for the award tightened during World War I for the Army version of the Medal of Honor, while the Navy version retained a non-combat provision until 1963.  In an Act of Congress of July 9, 1918, the War Department version of the medal required that the recipient "distinguish himself conspicuously by gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of his life above and beyond the call of duty," and also required that the act of valor be performed "in action involving actual conflict with an enemy."<ref name="Act of July 9, 1918, 40 Stat. 870">Act of July 9, 1918, 40 Stat. 870.</ref>  This was in reaction to the results of the Army Medal of Honor Review Board, which struck 911 names from the Medal of Honor Roll in February 1917 for lack of basic prerequisites.  These included the members of the 27th Maine erroneously awarded the medal for reenlisting to guard the capital during the Civil War, 29 members of Abraham Lincoln's funeral detail, and six civilians including Buffalo Bill Cody and Mary Walker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmohs.org/medal-history.php |title=History of the Medal of Honor |publisher=CMOHS.org |date= |accessdate=2012-11-15}}</ref>

* World War II: Starting in 1942, the Medal would only be awarded for action in combat, although the Navy version of the Medal of Honor technically allowed non-combat awards until 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/faqs/faq38-1.htm|title=The Navy's Medal of Honor|accessdate=January 26, 2012|publisher=US Navy}}</ref> Official accounts vary, but generally, the Medal of Honor for combat was known as the "Tiffany Cross", after [[Tiffany & Co.|the company that designed the medal]]. The Tiffany Cross was first awarded in 1919, but was unpopular partly because of its design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=7048|title="Tiffany" Medal of Honor Comes to Navy Museum|date=2003-04-27|last=Birnie|first=Michael|publisher=United States Navy|work=[[U.S. Navy Museum]]|accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> The Tiffany Cross Medal of Honor was awarded twice for non-combat. By a special authorized [[Act of Congress]], the medal was presented to Commander (later Rear Admiral) Richard Byrd and Floyd Bennett for their flight over the North Pole in 1926.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Above and Beyond: The Aviation Medals of Honor |first=Barrett |last=Tillman |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |location=Washington, D.C. |year=2003 |page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://encyclopediavirginia.org/media_player?mets_filename=evm00000779mets.xml |title=Encyclopedia Virginia |publisher=Encyclopedia Virginia |date=February 19, 1927 |accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> In 1942, the United States Navy reverted back to a single Medal of Honor, although the statute still contained a loophole allowing the award for both "action involving actual conflict with the enemy" or "in the line of his profession."<ref>"An Act to Amend the Act Approved February 4, 1919 (40 Stat. 1056)," August 7, 1942, Public Law 702, 56 Stat. 743-45."</ref> Arising from these criteria, approximately 60 percent of the medals earned during and after World War II have been awarded posthumously.<ref name="mohstats">{{cite web|month = May | year = 2003 |url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/mohstats.html |title = Medal of Honor Statistics |publisher = [[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate = July 23, 2006}}</ref>

* Public Law 88-77, July 25, 1963: The requirements for the Medal of Honor were standardized among all the services, requiring that a recipient had "distinguished himself conspicuously by gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of his life above and beyond the call of duty."<ref>"An Act to Amend Titles 10, 14, and 38, United States Code, with Respect to the Award of Certain Medals and the Medal of Honor Roll," July 25, 1956, HR 2998, Public Law 88-77, 77 Stat. 93.</ref>  Thus, the act removed the loophole allowing non-combat awards to Navy personnel. The act also clarified that the act of valor must occur during one of three circumstances:<ref>DoD Awards Manual 1348.33, V1, Oct. 12, 2011 (Nov. 23, 2010). p. 31--32, 8. Medal of Honor (1) (a) 1., 2., 3. (k),  ''p. 10, Title 10 US Code'' sections 3741, 6241, and 8741 (''Titles 14 & 38 not referenced by DoD'')</ref>
# While engaged in action against an enemy of the United States
# While engaged in military operations involving conflict with an opposing foreign force.
# While serving with friendly foreign forces engaged in an armed conflict against an opposing armed force in which the United States is not a belligerent party.<ref name="United States Code 1963">"An Act to Amend Titles 10, 14, and 38, United States Code, with Respect to the Award of Certain Medals and the Medal of Honor Roll," July 25, 1963, HR 2998, Public Law 88-77, 77 Stat. 93.</ref><ref>DoD Manual 1348.33, V1, Oct. 12. 2011 (Nov. 23, 2010), p. 31 & 32, 8. Medal of Honor (1) (a) 3. (k), ''p.10, Title 10 US Code'' sections 3741, 6241, and 8741 (''Title 14 & 38 not referenced By DoD'').</ref> 

Congress drew the three permutations of combat from President Kennedy's executive order of April 25, 1962, which previously added the same criteria to the Purple Heart. On August 24, Kennedy added similar criteria for the Bronze Star Medal.<ref name="HR2998 1963">"Subcommittee No.2 Consideration of HR2998, A Bill to Amend Titles 10, 14, and 38, United States Code, with Respect to the Award of Certain Medals and the Medal of Honor Roll," House of Representatives, Committee of Armed Services, June 6, 1963.</ref><ref>Executive order 11046 - DoD Awards Manual 1348.33, V3, Oct. 12, 2011 (Nov. 23, 2010), p. 19--21, 4. Bronze Star Medal (Title 10 & 37 is referenced by DoD, Titles 14 & 38 is not referenced by DoD)</ref>  The amendment was necessary because Cold War armed conflicts did not qualify for consideration under previous statutes such as the 1918 Army Medal of Honor Statute that required valor "in action involving actual conflict with an enemy," since the United States has not formally declared war since World War II as a result of the provisions of the United Nations Charter.<ref>"An Act Making Appropriations for the Support of the Army for the Fiscal Year Ending June Thirtieth, Nineteen Hundred and Nineteen," July 9, 1918, HR12281, Public Law 193, 40 Stat. 870.</ref>  According to congressional testimony by the Army's Deputy Chief of Staff for Personnel, the services were seeking authority to award the Medal of Honor and other valor awards retroactive to July 1, 1958, in areas such as Berlin, Lebanon, Quemoy and Matsu Islands, Taiwan Straits, Congo, Laos, Vietnam, and Cuba.<ref name="HR2998 1963"/>  

Note: In 1968, Navy Captain [[William McGonagle]] (1925<U+2013>1999) was awarded the Medal of Honor for his actions during the [[USS Liberty incident|USS ''Liberty'' incident]] on June 8--9, 1967. This ''friendly fire'' incident occurred during the Arab-Israeli [[Six Day War]] (June 5--10, 1967).<ref name="Liberty1">{{cite web|month = July | year = 2003 |url = http://www.nsa.gov/liberty/ |title = USS Liberty |publisher = National Security Agency, Central Security Service |accessdate = July 23, 2006|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060721005215/http://www.nsa.gov/liberty/ |archivedate = July 21, 2006|deadurl=yes}} audio and transcripts</ref><ref name="Liberty2">{{cite web|url = http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/sh-usn/usnsh-l/agtr5.htm |title = USS Liberty |publisher = Naval Historical Center |accessdate = July 23, 2006}} audio and transcripts</ref>

==Authority and privileges==
[[File:C-Chatanooga Cemetery2.jpg|220px|thumb|Medal of Honor monument and Medal of Honor headstones of the Civil War recipients of "Andrews Raid" at the [[Chattanooga National Cemetery]] in Chattanooga, Tennessee.]][[File:Jimmie W. Monteith Jr. Gravemarker 03.jpg|thumb|right|Medal of Honor gravemarker of a recipient at the [[Normandy American Cemetery and Memorial]]]]
[[File:James H Robinson grave.jpg|thumb|Medal of Honor headstone of a recipient at the [[Memphis National Cemetery]]]]

The four specific authorizing statutes amended July 25, 1963:<ref name="United States Code 1963"/>
* Army - {{UnitedStatesCode|10|3741}}
* Navy and Marine Corps - {{UnitedStatesCode|10|6241}}
* Air Force - {{UnitedStatesCode|10|8741}}
* Coast Guard - {{UnitedStatesCode|14|491}} (a version authorized but never awarded)<ref name=navyfaq>{{cite
web|url=http://www.navy.mil/moh/faq.html |title=Medal of Honor, Frequently Asked Questions |publishers=Navy.mil |date= |accessdate=May 12,
2012}}</ref>

''The President may award, and present in the name of Congress, a medal of honor of appropriate design, with ribbons and appurtenances, to a person who while a member of the Army'' (naval service; Navy and Marine Corps) (Air Force) (Coast Guard), ''distinguished himself conspicuously by gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of his life above and beyond the call of duty.''<ref name="1998code">{{cite web|date = January 26, 1998 |url = http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/uscode10/usc_sec_10_00003741----000-.html |title = Sec. 3741. Medal of honor: award |publisher =Cornell University |accessdate = January 26, 2012}}</ref>

===Privileges and courtesies===
The Medal of Honor confers special privileges on its recipients. By law, recipients have several benefits:<ref name="benefits">{{cite web|url = http://www.tricare.mil/mybenefit/home/overview/Eligibility/WhoIsEligible?kw=Medal+of+Honor+Recipients+and+Their+Families |title = Medal of Honor Recipients |publisher = Tricare |accessdate = May 16, 2012}}</ref><ref name="benefits3">{{cite web|url = http://www.vba.va.gov/bln/21/Rates/special1.htm |title = Special Benefits and Allowances Table |publisher = Dept. of Veterans Affairs |accessdate = July 24, 2006}}</ref>

* Each Medal of Honor recipient may have his or her name entered on the Medal of Honor Roll ({{UnitedStatesCode|38|1560}}). Each person whose name is placed on the Medal of Honor Roll is certified to the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] as being entitled to receive a monthly pension above and beyond any military pensions or other benefits for which they may be eligible. The pension is subject to [[Cost of living#Other uses of the term "cost-of-living allowance"|cost-of-living increases]]; as of 2011, it is $1,237 a month.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.vba.va.gov/bln/21/Rates/special1.htm|title = Department of Veterans Affairs Special Allowances for Clothing, Automobiles, and Medal of Honor Pension}}</ref>

* Enlisted recipients of the Medal of Honor are entitled to a supplemental uniform allowance.<ref name="32USC578.9">{{usc|32|578.9}}</ref>

* Recipients receive special entitlements to air transportation under the provisions of DOD Regulation 4515.13-R. This benefit allows the recipient to travel as he or she deems fit across geographical locations, and allows the recipient's dependents to travel either Overseas-Overseas, Overseas-Continental US, or Continental US-Overseas when accompanied by the recipient.<ref>http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/451513r.pdf - Page 85</ref>

* Special identification cards and commissary and exchange privileges are provided for Medal of Honor recipients and their eligible dependents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.army.mil/medalofhonor/process.html |title=Process |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=21 December 2012 |work=Medal of Honor |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=28 January 2013 }}</ref>

* Recipients are granted eligibility for interment at [[Arlington National Cemetery]], if not otherwise eligible.<ref>32 CFR 553.15(d)(1)</ref>

* Fully qualified children of recipients are eligible for admission to the [[List of United States military schools and academies|United States military academies]] without regard to the nomination and quota requirements.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://webster-new.dmz.usna.edu/Admissions/stnommed.htm|title = USNA. Admissions}}</ref>

* Recipients receive a 10 percent increase in retired pay.<ref>{{UnitedStatesCode|10|3991}}</ref>.

* Those awarded the medal after October 23, 2002, receive a Medal of Honor Flag. The law specified that all 103 living prior recipients as of that date would receive a flag. <ref>{{UnitedStatesCode|14|505}})</ref>

* Recipients receive an invitation to all future [[United States presidential inauguration|presidential inaugurations]] and [[United States presidential inaugural balls|inaugural balls]].<ref name="cnnGiunta">{{cite news| url= http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/02/08/army.medal/ | title= America's newest Medal of Honor recipient is leaving the Army | date= February 8, 2011 | publisher=CNN | accessdate= February 9, 2011| first=Larry| last= Shaughnessy| quote= Even though he's leaving the Army, Giunta is entitled to a number of special benefits reserved for Medal of Honor recipients, including a monthly Veterans Affairs pension of more than $1,237 a month for life as well as an invitation to every presidential inauguration and inauguration party.}}</ref>

* As with all medals, retired personnel may wear the Medal of Honor on "appropriate" civilian clothing. Regulations specify that recipients of the Medal of Honor are allowed to wear the uniform "at their pleasure" with standard restrictions on political, commercial, or extremist purposes (other former members of the armed forces may do so only at certain ceremonial occasions).<ref name="AR670">{{cite web|url = http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/r670_1.pdf|format=PDF|title = Wear and Appearance of Army Uniforms and Insignia |page= 316 |publisher = Department of the Army |accessdate = September 21, 2011}}</ref>

* Most states (40) offer a special license plate for certain types of vehicles to recipients at little or low cost to the recipient.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmv.de.gov/forms/veh_serv_forms/pdfs/ve_frm_valor.pdf |title=Application for Valor Specific License Plate |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 2001 |work=Delaware Division of Motor Vehicles |publisher=State of Delaware |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmv.state.pa.us/militarycenter/licenseplates.shtml |title=Military License Plate |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->  |work=Pennsylvania Department of Transportation |publisher=Commonwealth of Pennsylvania |accessdate=28 January 2013}}  <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.gov/mvc/Vehicle/MilitaryPersonnel.htm |title=Military personnel |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=31 January 2011 |work=Motor Vehicle Commission |publisher=State of New Jersey |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://statutes.laws.com/georgia/title-40/chapter-2/article-3/40-2-68 |title=<U+00A7> 40-2-68 - Special license plates for Medal of Honor winners |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2010|work=Georgia Statutes |publisher=Laws.com |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Connecticut.html |title=State / Territory Benefits - Connecticut |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=13 February 2012 |work=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.mass.gov/rmv/veteran/honor.htm |title=Congressional Medal of Honor Plates |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2012 |work=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.mva.maryland.gov/Vehicle-Services/SpecialtyPlates/MilitPlates_Entry.asp |title=Military Related Plates |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work=Department of Transportation |publisher=State of Maryland |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.scdmvonline.com/dmvnew/plategallery.aspx |title=Plate Galleries |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2007 |work=South Carolina Department of Motor Vehicles  |publisher=State of South Carolina |accessdate=28 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmv.virginia.gov/exec/vehicle/splates/info.asp?idnm=LVU |title=Special Plates: Plate Information |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2012 |work=Virginia Department of Motor Vehicles |publisher=Commonwealth of Virginia |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmv.ny.gov/military.htm |title=Custom Plate Gallery - Military and Veterans |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |work=New York State Department of Motor Vehicles |publisher=State of New York |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdot.gov/download/dmv/Plates_MVR33A.pdf |title=Military/Veteran<U+2019>s Registration Plate Application |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=January 2012 |work=North Carolina Division of Motor Vehicles |publisher=State of North Carolina |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Kentucky.html |title=State / Territory Benefits - Kentucky |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=9 January 2013 |work=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.tn.gov/revenue/vehicle/licenseplates/militarymemorial/military.shtml |title=Specialty License Plates - Military/Memorial |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work=Department of Revenue |publisher=State of Tennessee |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://bmv.ohio.gov/g_cmoh.stm |title=Congressional Medal of Honor |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work=Ohio Bureau of Motor Vehicles |publisher=State of Ohio |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://web01.dps.louisiana.gov/omv1.nsf/58c968bd569b099986256cdc000806eb/38d533205d0135dc862564af00649d33?OpenDocument |title=Congressional Medal of Honor License Plates |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1 December 2012 |work=Office of Motor Vehicles |publisher=State of Louisiana |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.in.gov/bmv/files/IGWT_Medal_of_Honor_and_Customer_Choices.pdf |title=BMV news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=20 December 2011 |work=Bureau of Motor Vehicles |publisher=State of Indiana |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://law.justia.com/codes/alabama/2009/Title32/Chapter6/32-6-231_1.html |title=Section 32-6-231.1 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2009 |work=2009 Alabama Code |publisher=Justia.com |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.maine.gov/sos/kids/maine-government/licenseplates.htm |title=Maine License Plates |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2007 |work=Secretary of State |publisher=State of Maine |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://dor.mo.gov/forms/4601.pdf |title=Application for Missouri Military Personalized License Plates |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=20 August 2012 |work=Missouri Department of Revenue |publisher=State of Missouri |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.dfa.arkansas.gov/offices/motorVehicle/Pages/specialityPlatesCategory.aspx?category=Military |title=Military Speciality Plates and Placards  |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2011 |work=Arkansas Department of Finance and Administration |publisher=State of Arkansas |accessdate=30 January 2013}} <br/>{{cite web |url=http://www.michigan.gov/sos/0,4670,7-127-1585_1595_1598-158232--,00.html |title=Medal of Honor |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |yea