===Double recipients===
Nineteen men have been awarded the Medal of Honor twice. Five of these men were awarded both the Army and Navy Medal of Honor for the same action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/mohstats.html |title=Medal of Honor Statistics |publisher=History.army.mil |date= |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Since February 1919, no single individual can be awarded more than one Medal of Honor for the same action, although a member of one branch of the armed forces can receive the Medal of Honor from another branch if the actions for which it was awarded occurred under the authority of the second branch.<ref>{{cite book|title=1919 Supplement to United States Complied Statutes, 1918|year=1919|publisher=West Publishing Company |pages=30, 49|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=A9MZAAAAYAAJ&dq|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> To date, the maximum number of Medals of Honor earned by any service member has been two.<ref name=navyfaq/>

:<small> <U+00A7> Rank refers to rank held at time of Medal of Honor action.</small>
