Since 1979, 50 belated Medal of Honor decorations have been made to recognize actions from the Civil War to the Vietnam War<ref>''[http://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/RL30011.pdf Medal of Honor recipients 1979<U+2013>2007]''. Julissa Gomez-Granger, Congressional Research Service Report for Congress</ref> The most recent of these occurred on May 16, 2012, when President Barack Obama presented the Medal of Honor posthumously to Army Sergeant [[Leslie H. Sabo, Jr.]] for conspicuous gallantry in action on May 10, 1970, near [[Tonl<U+00E9> San|Se San]], [[Cambodia]], during the Vietnam War<ref name=cbsnews5-16-12>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57435607/gi-killed-in-vietnam-war-receives-medal-of-honor/ |title=GI killed in Vietnam War receives Medal of Honor |publisher=CBS News |date= |accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref> and on May 2, 2011, when he presented the Medal of Honor posthumously to Army Private First Class [[Henry Svehla]] and Army Private First Class [[Anthony T. Kaho<U+02BB>ohanohano]] for their heroic actions during the Korean War.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Marsh |first=Wendell |title=Two Korean War vets receive Medal of Honor posthumously |publisher=Reuters |date=May 2, 2011 |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/02/us-obama-medals-idUSTRE7416NA20110502 |archiveurl =http://www.webcitation.org/5ySuVarC7 |archivedate= May 5, 2011}}</ref>

==27th Maine and other revoked awardings==
[[File:Medal of Honor monument, Austin, TX IMG 2206.JPG|right|thumb|A Medal of Honor monument at the [[Texas State Cemetery]] in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Texas]]]]

During the Civil War, [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Edwin M. Stanton]] promised a Medal of Honor to every man in the [[27th Maine Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] who extended his enlistment beyond the agreed-upon date. The Battle of Gettysburg was imminent, and 311 men of the regiment volunteered to serve until the battle was resolved. The remaining men returned to Maine, but with the Union victory at Gettysburg the 311 volunteers soon followed. The volunteers arrived back in Maine in time to be discharged with the men who had earlier returned. Since there seemed to be no official list of the 311 volunteers, the [[United States Department of War|War Department]] exacerbated the situation by forwarding 864 medals to the commanding officer of the regiment. The commanding officer only issued the medals to the volunteers who stayed behind and retained the others on the grounds that, if he returned the remainder to the War Department, the War Department would try to reissue the medals.<ref name="MWxix">{{harvnb|Mikaelian|Wallace|2003|p=xix}}</ref>

In 1916, a board of five Army generals on the retired list convened under act of law to review every Army Medal of Honor awarded. The board was to report on any Medals of Honor awarded or issued for any cause other than distinguished service. The commission, led by [[Nelson A. Miles]], identified 911 awards for causes other than distinguished service. This included the 864 medals awarded to members of the 27th Maine regiment, 29 who served as Abraham Lincoln's funeral guard, six civilians, including Dr. Mary Edwards Walker and [[Buffalo Bill|Buffalo Bill Cody]], and 12 others.<ref name="MWxxv">{{harvnb|Mikaelian|Wallace|2003|p=xxv}}</ref><ref name=CD15>{{harvnb|Collier|Del Calzo|2006|p=15}}</ref> Dr. Walker's medal was restored by President [[Jimmy Carter]] in 1977.<ref name="walker"/> Cody and four other civilian scouts who rendered distinguished service in action, and who were therefore considered by the board to have fully earned their medals, had theirs restored in 1989.<ref name=CD16>{{harvnb|Collier|Del Calzo|2006|p=16}}</ref> The report was endorsed by the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps|Judge Advocate General]], who also advised that the War Department should not seek the return of the revoked medals from the recipients identified by the board. In the case of recipients who continued to wear the medal, the War Department was advised to take no action to enforce the statute.<ref>66th Congress 1st Session, Document 58, General Staff and Medals of Honor, ordered to be printed 23 July 1919.</ref>

==Past racial discrimination==
* A 1993 study commissioned by the U.S. Army investigated racial discrimination in the awarding of medals.<ref name="African">{{cite web|url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/mohb.html |title = WWII African American MOH recipients |publisher= [[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate = July 20, 2006}}</ref> At the time, no Medals of Honor had been awarded to American soldiers of [[African descent]] who served in World War II. After an exhaustive review of files, the study recommended that ten of their [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] recipients be awarded the Medal of Honor. On January 13, 1997, President [[Bill Clinton]] presented the Medal of Honor to seven of these World War II veterans, six of them posthumously.  With the passing of [[Vernon Baker]], a former [[U.S. Infantry]] [[Officer (armed forces)|Officer]] on July 13, 2010, all of these recipients are deceased.<ref name=CD25/>

* In 1998, a similar study of [[Asian American]]s resulted in President [[Bill Clinton]] presenting 21 Medals of Honor in 2000. Twenty of these medals went to American soldiers of [[Japanese people|Japanese]] descent of the [[442nd Regimental Combat Team]] that served in the [[European Theater of Operations]] during World War II. One of these Medal of Honor recipients was Senator from Hawaii, [[Daniel Inouye]], a former U.S. Infantry officer.<ref name=CD25>{{harvnb|Collier|Del Calzo|2006|p=25}}</ref>

* In 2005, President [[George W. Bush]] presented the Medal of Honor to [[Tibor Rubin]], a [[Jewish American]] who was a [[Holocaust survivor]] of World War II and U.S. Infantry [[POW]] of the [[Korean War]] whom many believed to have been overlooked because of his [[religion]].<ref name="Asian">{{cite web|last =Williams |first = Rdui |date = May 19, 2000 |url = http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=45192 |title = 21 Asian American World War II Vets to Get Medal of Honor |work = American Forces Press Service News Articles |publisher = Department of Defense |accessdate = July 21, 2008}}</ref><ref name="JewishLib">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/tibor_rubin.html|title=Tibor Rubin|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>

==Similar decorations within the United States==
The following United States decorations, in one degree or another, bear similar names to the Medal of Honor, but are entirely separate awards with different criteria for issuance:

* [[Cardenas Medal of Honor]]: decoration of the [[Revenue Cutter Service]], merged into the [[United States Coast Guard]]

* [[Chaplain's Medal for Heroism]]: awarded posthumously for a single action to [[Four Chaplains|four recipients]]

* [[Congressional Gold Medal]]: the highest civilian honor bestowed by the United States (along with the Presidential Medal of Freedom)

* [[Congressional Space Medal of Honor]]: intended for issuance to astronauts, but despite its name, it is not equal to the Medal of Honor

* [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]: the highest civilian honor bestowed by the United States (along with the Congressional Gold Medal)

* The [[Southern Cross of Honor]]: a military decoration meant to honor the officers, noncommissioned officers, and privates of the [[Confederate States of America]] for their valor in the armed forces during the [[American Civil War]]. It was formally approved by the [[Congress of the Confederate States]] on October 13, 1862,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.jmu.edu/special/manuscripts/2060_UDC_CrossofHonor.aspx |title=A Guide to the United Daughters of the Confederacy Southern Cross of Honor Documents |publisher=James Madison University Libraries |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> and was originally intended to be on par with the Union Army's Medal of Honor.

Several [[United States law enforcement decorations]] bear the name "Medal of Honor". The [[Public Safety Officer Medal of Valor]], established by Congress in 2001, stated to be "the highest National award for valor by a public safety officer", is also awarded by the President of the US.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.medalofvalor.gov/ |title=Public Safety Officer Medal of Valor
|publisher=Bureau of Justice Assistance |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref>

